I'm running Arch Linux with gnome-shell 3.34.1 (at present) on an HP Pavilion with a touchscreen. It's getting rather annoying to have to patch out the OSK every update. Can a system setting please be implemented to disable the OSK except upon request be implemented?

Just for anyone who hates the OSK so much they're willing to patch it every update, here's the modified code for `js/ui/keyboard.js` that disables the OSK:
```javascript
    _lastDeviceIsTouchscreen() {
        //if (!this._lastDeviceId)
            return false;

        let manager = Clutter.DeviceManager.get_default();
        let device = manager.get_device(this._lastDeviceId);

        if (!device)
            return false;

        return device.get_device_type() == Clutter.InputDeviceType.TOUCHSCREEN_DEVICE;
    }

    _syncEnabled() {
        let wasEnabled = false/*this._enabled*/;
        this._enableKeyboard = false/*this._a11yApplicationsSettings.get_boolean(SHOW_KEYBOARD)*/;
        this._enabled = this._enableKeyboard || this._lastDeviceIsTouchscreen();
        if (!this._enabled && !this._keyboardController)
            return;

        if (this._enabled && !this._keyboardController)
            this._setupKeyboard();
        else if (!this._enabled)
            this.setCursorLocation(null);

        if (!this._enabled && wasEnabled)
            Main.layoutManager.hideKeyboard(true);
    }
```

Also, no segfaults if

- open & close libgobject first
- open `pango` first but do not close, i.e.
```
#include <dlfcn.h>
#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {

    void *handle;
    void *handle2;

    handle = dlopen("/path/to/libpango-1.0.dylib",RTLD_LAZY);
    handle2 = dlopen("/path/to/libgobject-2.0.dylib",RTLD_LAZY);

    cout<<dlclose(handle)<<endl;
    cout<<dlclose(handle2)<<endl;

    return 0;
}
```

@behdad Maybe if you are only writing c code and only using glib/pango; however, this comes up when used in other languages as shared libraries, in this case, using cairo/gtk in julia, where external libraries/dependencies are checked for validity/existence by dlopen (and optionally calling some functions), followed by dlclose. Since that dependency checking/auto install process is designed to be general and cross-platform, it would be a little awkward to add special code for glib/pango. All these works until a couple of weeks ago following an update to glib or pango/pangocario, where it has been cause segfaults, see relevant github discussion here:

https://github.com/JuliaGraphics/Cairo.jl/issues/271

