@Jehan 
> "Only select colors from these colors in the palette", allowing opacity painting, antialiasing, gradation or other operations within certain colors only, hence keeping the colors semantic.

That is the approach taken by GrafX2 (and probably also other pixeling programs which support indexpainting).
Rightclicking on the "Pal" button gives a dialog in which one option is 'Colors for best match'. This brings up a 'palette' where you can leftclick to exclude that color, rightclick to include it. Clicking on a color in the image while this dialog is up, performs the same include or exclude action.

It also includes a 'Stencil' function, which is kind of the opposite: specify that particular colors can/cannot be modified by painting actions.

This may certainly not seem 'minimal', but the point was that GrafX2 is a mature program that has dealt with this problem from an early point in its development, and these are the solutions it arrived at.

@ell 

Sounds ok as long as the error interval is carefully chosen. The most iffy thing would be these images with padded palettes (eg. palette is 256 colors, but only the first 16 are used, the rest are the same duplicate color -- black is common). That could break things, although I think you'd have to go out of your way to actually become inconvenienced by it.

@Nyerguds Maybe it wasn't worth it. Personally (aside from any utility I get out of indexpainting), I think the unification of user experience achieved by making this change was very important. I was often frustrated in the past that tools either plain didn't work in indexed mode, or didn't work in a way that was obviously close to how they would work on GRAY or RGB images. So, I would make a duplicate, convert it to RGB, do the operation, then copy+paste it back.

